President Obama has announced his intent to nominate John Morton as the Executive Vice President of the Overseas Private Investment Corporation (OPIC). Morton is currently the Chief of Staff of OPIC. Prior to his current position, he served as the Vice President for Investment Policy at OPIC and as the Managing Director of the Pew Economic Policy Group at The Pew Charitable Trusts. Morton also has experience in national security policy and investment management. He holds a B.A. from Harvard College, an M.A. from The John Hopkins University, and an M.B.A. from The Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania.

President Obama has also announced his intent to appoint Nancy M. Schlichting as the Chairperson of the Commission on Care. Schlichting is the CEO of the Henry Ford Health System and has held various leadership roles in hospital management. She serves on the board of several organizations, including the Kresge Foundation and the Walgreen Co. Schlichting holds an A.B. from Duke University and an M.B.A. from Cornell University.

David W. Gorman has been appointed as a member of the Commission on Care. Gorman previously served as the Executive Director of the National Service and Legislative Headquarters of the Disabled American Veterans (DAV). He is a combat disabled veteran of the Vietnam War.

Dr. Joyce M. Johnson has also been appointed as a member of the Commission on Care. She is a physician and consultant in private practice. Dr. Johnson has served in various senior management positions in the U.S. Public Health Service (USPHS) and has clinical experience in mental health and epidemiology. She received her B.A. from Luther College, an M.A. from the University of Iowa, and a D.O. from Michigan State University.